Java is a widely used, object-oriented programming language known for portability, security, and reliability.
Below are the main features of Java explained simply.

1. Platform Independent (Write Once, Run Anywhere)
        Java programs are compiled into bytecode, which runs on the Java Virtual Machine.
        This means a Java program written on one system can run on any system that has JVM.
Example: Windows, Linux, and macOS can all run the same Java program.

2. Object-Oriented
        Java follows Object-Oriented Programming principles such as:
        ->Encapsulation
        ->Inheritance
        ->Polymorphism
        ->Abstraction
 This helps in building modular and reusable code.

3. Simple
        Java removed complex features from languages like C++, such as:
        ->Pointers
        ->Operator overloading
        ->Multiple inheritance (via classes)
This makes Java easier to learn and safer.

4. Secure
        Java provides strong security because:
         ->No direct memory access
         ->Bytecode verification
         ->Security manager
         ->Sandboxing
This is why Java is often used in network and web applications.

5. Robust
        Java is considered robust because of:
        ->Strong memory management
        ->Exception handling
        ->Automatic Garbage Collection
Garbage collection automatically removes unused objects from memory.

6. Multithreaded
        Java supports multithreading, meaning multiple tasks can run simultaneously within a program.
        This improves performance in applications like games, servers, and real-time systems.

7. High Performance
        Although Java is interpreted by JVM, it uses Just-In-Time (JIT) compilation to improve performance.

8. Distributed
        Java supports distributed computing with libraries for networking such as:
        ->Socket programming
        ->Remote Method Invocation (RMI)
This makes it suitable for internet-based applications.

9. Portable
       Java programs behave consistently across platforms because primitive data types have fixed sizes.

10. Dynamic
       Java can dynamically load classes during runtime, making applications more flexible.



